Dyce quotes Reed, who says that Dryden borrowed from the following passage of Webster :—

Flumineo. What hast got, But, like the wealth of captains, a poor handful, Which in thy palm thou bear'st as men hold water? Seeking to gripe it fast, the frail reward Steals through thy fingers.

“The White Devil,” ll. 1102-6, p. 19, col. 1.

Reed can hardly be right, because Dryden’s figure is that of a man grasping snow, which melts away in his hand. Montaigne and Sir Philip Sidney both use Webster's figure, and Webster was perfectly ac- quainted with both authors. It is also in Marston :—
